<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06255284 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06255284 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: (Pizza with info-box containing above text) (color)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; JUVENILE; SCHOOL; FOOD; DIET; PROTEST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  If your 8-year-old could eat hot dogs or double-cheese pepperoni pizza atevery meal, including school lunch, then he or she is a typical Americanchild. And that's the problem, says an advocacy group that wants thegovernment to make sure that school lunches meet federal nutrition standards.;  &quot;Elementary school-age children (from) all income groups consume alarminglyhigh levels of fat, saturated fat and cholesterol,&quot; said a report issued todayby Public Voice for Food and Health Policy.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SCHOOL LUNCHES CALLED SATURATED WITH JUNKY FOOD  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related articles on pages 6A and 1B of this section.; Additionalinformation attached to the end of this article  </MEMO><TEXT>     Phil Shanholtzer, spokesman for the federal school lunch program, said&quot;Public Voice gives us this blast every year . . . &quot;;   &quot;We've done a lot overthe years to improve the commodities we provide,&quot; Shanholtzer said.;   Whilethe nutrition debate continues, no one disputes that the cost of studentlunches is rising -- by as much as a quarter at many Bay Area schools.; Kids'nutrition; Elementary school-age children are consuming high levels of fat,saturated fat and cholesterol.; Children get 36.5% of their total caloriesfrom fat. The U.S.D.A recommends no more than 30%; They get 14.1% of theircalories from saturated fat (meat products). Recommended: 10%; At 143.5milligrams per 1,000 calories, their daily cholesterol intake is 43.5% higherthan the recommended 100 milligrams.; Source: Public Voice For Food And HealthPolicy  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910911  </PUBD